        <headline>Special Weather Statement issued April 24 at 4:12PM CDT by NWS Fort Worth TX</headline>
        <description>At 412 PM CDT, Doppler radar was tracking strong thunderstorms along
a line extending from 7 miles northwest of Camp Creek Lake to near
Thrall. Movement was southeast at 30 mph.

HAZARD...Wind gusts up to 50 mph and nickel size hail.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Gusty winds could knock down tree limbs and blow around
unsecured objects. Minor damage to outdoor objects is
possible.

Strong thunderstorms will be near...
Thorndale, Calvert, and Franklin around 415 PM CDT.
Hearne, Rockdale, and Camp Creek Lake around 420 PM CDT.
Alcoa Lake around 425 PM CDT.

Other locations impacted by these storms include Minerva, Hanover,
San Gabriel, Sharp, Maysfield, Hoyte, Easterly, Crossroads, Benchley,
and Milano.

This includes Interstate 45 near mile marker 152.
</description>
        <instruction>If outdoors, consider seeking shelter inside a building.

Torrential rainfall is also occurring with these storms and may lead
to localized flooding. Do not drive your vehicle through flooded
roadways.

Frequent cloud to ground lightning is occurring with these storms.
Lightning can strike 10 miles away from a thunderstorm. Seek a safe
shelter inside a building or vehicle.

A Severe Thunderstorm Watch remains in effect until 800 PM CDT for
central Texas.</instruction>
